Anonymous Sat 12 Feb 2022 00:34:21 No.45469895 Report
Quoted By:
>>45469683
Kind of depends on the style. A lot of first person stuff works more like a running internal monologue than the MC functioning as a narrator, so they don't introduce themselves to the audience. But if the framing device is the MC telling his story to an audience you would expect that sort of aside where he could introduce himself. But stereotypical introductory sequences stand out like a sore thumb. Stuff like the MC just happening to look in a mirror and giving a perfect description of themselves. That just crushes suspension of disbelief. You want things to appear natural, especially with a first person narrative that gives insight to the MC's thought process. And that's another thing: We don't really need the name right away. We're already in the guy's head, so we're hardly going to mistake him for someone else.

>Do I wait until he interacts with someone
This is the most organic way to do it and is my go to because it has the benefit of also providing room for characterization. It doesn't have to be an interaction in real time, though. You could have the narrator divulge into their past by retelling a memory, or you can have them imagine an ideal version of themselves having a conversation in the future.
The nametag/license idea also works. One could adjoin it to a scene where they look at a photo of themselves or their reflection so you can get their physical descriptions out of the way in the same paragraph.
If the name has some kind of narrative or personal importance, you can make a strong cold open with it. Posting this as a practice exercise.
>The townsfolk call me Shaojao, or Burning Foot, on account of my deeds on the day the demons broke through the gates. With bare feet, I charged into a house set ablaze, rescuing the infant daughter of the mayor from her crib.
>The elders, once wary around me as they were every son of man, now greet me as they would a neighbor and friend. Their children, however, like to pull at the hem of my robe to ask about the scars that run along my ankles, their eyes wide with awe.

It's a song about seizing opportunity, which I guess is fitting for how she just fucking stuck herself in the show.

It's also about really FEELING the experience, not just having one. Like, what's the point of vacationing to a resort in Cancun if you're just going to live all comfy and American the whole time? Porsha lives in a fucking castle, she's got everything on her side which allows her to circumvent most personal growth. It's only when she disobeys her father, takes that risk, that she can begin to understand the emotional fulfillment that she's been missing.

It's exhilarating to be able to fail, to be insecure for once, and is the source of the "pride and shame" referenced in the song.

Is this level of introspection explored in the movie? Perhaps as a way of getting us to root for Porsha as a victim of circumstance? Not really. Would've made a great Rapunzel-style movie on its own. Too bad illumination shoehorned all these characters in so no one got more than superficial and insincere development. It's for this reason that you probably didn't understand why the fuck she was singing about the song. We had no moment wherein Porsha seriously considers life choices, so it feels anodyne.

TL;DR A Porsha movie would be pretty good if done right. However, it'll never be done right. You would've understood the song of illumination was capable of depth.
